# CNIG License v1.1 — Structural Framework Governance License
## Constraint-Native Infrastructure Governance (CNIG)

Copyright (c) 2026  
Gaurav H. Thanki  

---

## 1. Purpose

This license governs the use of:

Constraint-Native Infrastructure Governance (CNIG)

Authored by Gaurav H. Thanki.

CNIG is a conceptual framework for reasoning about admissible system states within reachable state space under composition constraints prior to execution.

It is intended for:

- systems interpretation
- architectural reasoning
- research and academic analysis
- conceptual discussion of distributed systems behavior

CNIG is not a system, product, methodology, or execution framework.

---

## 2. Nature of CNIG

CNIG is:

- a conceptual reasoning model  
- a vocabulary for compositional system analysis  
- a lens for describing emergent behavior in distributed systems  

CNIG is not:

- a runtime system  
- a policy enforcement engine  
- a compliance framework  
- a formal verification system  
- a design implementation standard  

CNIG does not imply the existence, requirement, or feasibility of any software implementation.

---

## 3. Permitted Use

CNIG may be used for:

- reading and interpretation  
- academic research and citation  
- systems design discussion (conceptual only)  
- architectural review and analysis  
- non-commercial experimentation  
- internal discussion of system behavior as a conceptual reference  

All usage must comply with Sections 5 and 6.

CNIG must not be treated as an operational framework in any environment.

---

## 4. Commercial Context Use

CNIG may be referenced in commercial environments only as a conceptual lens for analysis and design discussion.

It may NOT be:

- packaged as a product or feature  
- sold as a methodology, framework, or system  
- embedded as a governance or control mechanism  
- used as a branding replacement for engineering processes  
- converted into executable logic, workflows, or enforcement systems  

---

## 5.  Canonical Attribution Requirement

The canonical attribution for the framework is:

Constraint-Native Infrastructure Governance (CNIG) by Gaurav H. Thanki

This exact attribution should be used when:

- formally defining CNIG
- identifying the author or origin of CNIG
- providing a formal citation to CNIG
- reproducing or distributing substantial portions of the framework
- publishing a derivative conceptual framework that explicitly references CNIG

Attribution is not required for:

- every incidental mention of CNIG
- repeated references after attribution has already been established in the same document
- ordinary discussion or application of CNIG concepts where authorship is not the subject
- every use of an individual CNIG primitive, invariant, failure mode, or observation

Where attribution is required, it must not be removed, anonymized, or represented in a manner that assigns authorship of CNIG to another party.

---

## 6. Non-Authority Clause (CRITICAL HARDENING)

CNIG has no operational authority in any system in which it is referenced.

Specifically:

- CNIG may not be used to approve or deny system changes  
- CNIG may not be encoded into CI/CD gating logic  
- CNIG may not be implemented as runtime policy enforcement  
- CNIG may not be used as a compliance or certification mechanism  
- CNIG may not be treated as executable governance logic  

Any system referencing CNIG must treat it strictly as a conceptual model with no execution authority.

---

## 7. No Implementation Guarantee Clause

CNIG is theoretical and interpretive.

No guarantees are made regarding:

- implementability  
- correctness in software systems  
- completeness of modeling  
- suitability for production use  
- safety or operational outcomes  

Any attempt to implement or operationalize CNIG is an independent interpretation by the implementer.

---

## 8. Restriction Boundary

CNIG may not be represented as:

- a production governance system  
- a safety-certified system  
- a runtime enforcement mechanism  
- a formal verification framework  
- a deployable compliance system  

This applies regardless of modification, embedding, or derivative interpretation.

---

## 9. Epistemic Limitation

CNIG does not claim:

- implementation completeness  
- correctness guarantees  
- universal applicability  
- formal verification completeness  

CNIG is a conceptual lens for interpreting system composition behavior.

---

## 10. Liability Limitation

To the maximum extent permitted by applicable law:

The author is not liable for any outcomes arising from:

- use or interpretation of CNIG  
- system designs influenced by CNIG  
- operational decisions informed by CNIG  
- attempts to implement or adapt CNIG  
- production failures, losses, or damages associated with CNIG references  

All use is at the user’s own risk.

